description: From Penobscot senabe (“man”); compare Abenaki sanôba (“man”).

entries.meaning: (US) A male Native American, especially a married one; a brave.
examples: Chickatabot (the chief Sachem of the Massachusetts) comes with his sannups and squaws (that is, married men and their wives) to Boston, presents the governor with a hogshead of Indian corn.

entries.meaning: (US, Maine, colloquial) A mischievous male child.
